projects: [{'title': 'Heart vector-mediated gene therapy: towards a clinically applicable cure for inherited cardiomyopathies', 'date': {'start': {'month': 12, 'day': None, 'year': 2021}, 'end': {'month': None, 'day': None, 'year': None}}, 'description': 'The only way to cure a genetic disease is to correct the disease-causing mutation. Thus, ongoing research is focused on developing gene therapies to correct these mutations. Building upon our recent advances in understanding the complex genetics behind cardiomyopathies and viral vector-mediated therapies, we aim to provide a) the first preclinical proof-of-concept (PoC) therapy for PLN R14del-induced cardiomyopathy and, in doing so, b) gather knowledge and assemble a technology toolbox permitting accelerating therapeutic development for inherited cardiomyopathies. To this end, we will perform head-to-head comparisons of different gene therapy technologies in (i) an in vitro model based on PLN R14del patient-derived iPSC-CMs, and (ii) humanized mouse and porcine models carrying the PLN R14del mutation', 'contributors': [{'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'Mudit', 'last_name': 'Mishra, PhD', 'name': None, 'headline': 'Scientist at Batavia Biosciences l Cell & Gene Therapy I Drug Development I Biomarkers | Assays | Quality & Compliance'}]}, {'title': 'Cardiovascular Moonshot RegMed XB: Regeneration of the human heart', 'date': {'start': {'month': 12, 'day': None, 'year': 2019}, 'end': {'month': None, 'day': None, 'year': None}}, 'description': 'The cardiovascular moonshot of RegMed XB is a comprehensive program based on the concept that we should be able to create a cardiac (re-)generative therapy that suits best the individual patient. One approach is to restore the heart function outside of the body (ex vivo). The advantage of this method is that we can solely treat the heart and assess cardiac function during treatment. During the time the heart is outside the body, the body will be connected to a heart-lung machine. After restoring the heart, it will be re-implanted. With this approach, gene therapy to cure hereditary diseases will also become possible. The researchers aim to stimulate the body’s own regenerative capacity including, for example, improving the contractility and perfusion of the heart muscle, repair, or replacement of coronary arteries and heart valves.', 'contributors': [{'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'Mudit', 'last_name': 'Mishra, PhD', 'name': None, 'headline': 'Scientist at Batavia Biosciences l Cell & Gene Therapy I Drug Development I Biomarkers | Assays | Quality & Compliance'}]}, {'title': 'Development of clinical prediction models for cardiac allograft vasculopathy and late graft failure in heart transplant recipients- A clinical Study ', 'date': {'start': {'month': 7, 'day': None, 'year': 2015}, 'end': {'month': None, 'day': None, 'year': None}}, 'description': 'Most of the survival improvement in heart transplant recipients in the past three decades is related to mortality reduction during the first post-transplant year. Mortality beyond 1 year after transplant has only slightly declined for patients transplanted in the past 20 years. After the first year, cardiac allograft vasculopathy (CAV) and late graft failure are the most important cause of death in heart transplant recipients. On one hand, this project is directed at the development of prediction models of CAV and late graft failure. On the other hand, the objective is to improve our understanding of the pathophysiology of late graft failure and its relation with epicardial CAV, microvascular CAV, and low-grade myocardial injury.', 'contributors': [{'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'Mudit', 'last_name': 'Mishra, PhD', 'name': None, 'headline': 'Scientist at Batavia Biosciences l Cell & Gene Therapy I Drug Development I Biomarkers | Assays | Quality & Compliance'}]}, {'title': 'High-density lipoprotein-targeted therapies for heart failure with preserved ejection fraction (HFpEF).', 'date': {'start': {'month': 6, 'day': None, 'year': 2015}, 'end': {'month': None, 'day': None, 'year': None}}, 'description': 'Heart failure is the cardiovascular epidemic of the 21st century.  This syndrome is a growing public health problem, the leading cause of hospitalization, and a major cause of mortality. Plasma high-density lipoprotein (HDL) cholesterol levels and levels of its major apolipoprotein (apo), apo A-I, are inversely correlated with the incidence of coronary heart disease. HDLs exert divergent functions that include actions mediated by HDL receptor ecto-F1-ATPase coupled to purinergic P2Y receptors, scavenger receptor class B, type I (SR-BI), and/or receptor activation by HDL cargo molecules. These pleiotropic properties offer perspectives for new therapeutic areas for HDL-targeted interventions. The general objective of this project is to study the effect of administration of apo A-I Milano/phospholipid complexes (HDL Milano) and hepatocyte-directed AAV8-mediated apo A-I gene transfer in murine models of HFpEF. ', 'contributors': [{'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'Mudit', 'last_name': 'Mishra, PhD', 'name': None, 'headline': 'Scientist at Batavia Biosciences l Cell & Gene Therapy I Drug Development I Biomarkers | Assays | Quality & Compliance'}]}, {'title': 'Mesenchymal Stem Cell Therapy in Myocardial Infarction, Stoke, Renal Failure and Diabetes', 'date': {'start': {'month': None, 'day': None, 'year': 2013}, 'end': {'month': None, 'day': None, 'year': 2013}}, 'description': None, 'contributors': [{'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'Mudit', 'last_name': 'Mishra, PhD', 'name': None, 'headline': 'Scientist at Batavia Biosciences l Cell & Gene Therapy I Drug Development I Biomarkers | Assays | Quality & Compliance'}]}, {'title': 'Cell penetrating peptides and Antimicrobial peptides, nanoparticle (CPP) mediated therapeutics.', 'date': {'start': {'month': 7, 'day': None, 'year': 2013}, 'end': {'month': 5, 'day': None, 'year': 2015}}, 'description': None, 'contributors': [{'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'Mudit', 'last_name': 'Mishra, PhD', 'name': None, 'headline': 'Scientist at Batavia Biosciences l Cell & Gene Therapy I Drug Development I Biomarkers | Assays | Quality & Compliance'}]}]
